---
import Callout from "../components/Callout.astro";
import DiagramBox from "../components/DiagramBox.astro";
import SequenceDiagram from "../components/SequenceDiagram.astro";
import CodeBlock from "../components/CodeBlock.astro";
import RunsBadge from "../components/RunsBadge.astro";

const serverComponentCode = `<span class="text-violet-300">import </span><span class="text-zinc-400">{ </span><span class="text-sky-300">db</span><span class="text-zinc-400"> } </span><span class="text-violet-300">from </span><span class="text-emerald-400">'@/lib/database'</span><span class="text-zinc-400">;</span>

<span class="text-zinc-400">// This runs on the SERVER. The browser never</span>
<span class="text-zinc-400">// sees this code or your database credentials.</span>

<span class="text-violet-300">export default async function </span><span class="text-amber-300">PostsPage</span><span class="text-zinc-400">() {</span>
<span class="text-zinc-400">  // Query the database directly — no API layer needed</span>
<span class="text-zinc-400">  </span><span class="text-violet-300">const </span><span class="text-sky-300">posts</span><span class="text-zinc-400"> = </span><span class="text-violet-300">await </span><span class="text-sky-300">db</span><span class="text-zinc-400">.</span><span class="text-sky-300">query</span><span class="text-zinc-400">(</span>
<span class="text-zinc-400">    </span><span class="text-emerald-400">\`SELECT id, title, author
     FROM posts
     ORDER BY created_at DESC\`</span>
<span class="text-zinc-400">  );</span>

<span class="text-zinc-400">  // This JSX is rendered to HTML on the server,</span>
<span class="text-zinc-400">  // then sent to the browser as a complete page.</span>
<span class="text-zinc-400">  </span><span class="text-violet-300">return </span><span class="text-zinc-400">(</span>
<span class="text-zinc-400">    &lt;</span><span class="text-red-400">ul</span><span class="text-zinc-400">&gt;</span>
<span class="text-zinc-400">      {</span><span class="text-sky-300">posts</span><span class="text-zinc-400">.</span><span class="text-sky-300">map</span><span class="text-zinc-400">(post =&gt;</span>
<span class="text-zinc-400">        &lt;</span><span class="text-red-400">li</span><span class="text-amber-300"> key</span><span class="text-zinc-400">={post.id}&gt;</span>
<span class="text-zinc-400">          {post.title} — {post.author}</span>
<span class="text-zinc-400">        &lt;/</span><span class="text-red-400">li</span><span class="text-zinc-400">&gt;</span>
<span class="text-zinc-400">      )}</span>
<span class="text-zinc-400">    &lt;/</span><span class="text-red-400">ul</span><span class="text-zinc-400">&gt;</span>
<span class="text-zinc-400">  );</span>
<span class="text-zinc-400">}</span>`;
---

<div class="space-y-8">
  <p class="text-lg leading-relaxed text-zinc-300">
    So far, every tool we've discussed falls clearly on one side: the
    bundler runs on your machine, React runs in the browser, the API runs on
    a server.
    <strong class="text-teal-300">Fullstack frameworks</strong> like
    Next.js and Remix deliberately blur that line — they let you write React
    code that runs on <em>both</em> the server and the client.
  </p>

  {/* The problem CSR has */}
  <div class="space-y-4">
    <h3 class="font-display font-bold text-teal-300 text-xl">
      The Problem with Client-Side Rendering
    </h3>
    <p class="text-zinc-400 leading-relaxed">
      With a pure client-side React app (what Vite gives you), here's what
      happens when someone visits your page:
    </p>

    <div class="rounded-xl border border-zinc-800 bg-zinc-900/50 p-6">
      <SequenceDiagram
        steps={[
          {
            from: "Browser",
            to: "Server",
            label:
              'Requests the page — server sends back a nearly empty HTML file with just a <div id="root"></div>',
            color: "#a78bfa",
          },
          {
            from: "Browser",
            to: "Server",
            label:
              "Downloads the JavaScript bundle (could be 200KB+ gzipped for a large app)",
            color: "#a78bfa",
          },
          {
            from: "Browser",
            to: "Browser",
            label:
              "Parses and executes the JS — React builds the page from scratch. User sees a blank screen or spinner until this finishes.",
            color: "#fb923c",
          },
          {
            from: "Browser",
            to: "API Server",
            label:
              "React realizes it needs data, fires off fetch() calls — more waiting",
            color: "#fb923c",
          },
          {
            from: "Browser",
            to: "User",
            label:
              "Finally renders the complete page. On slow connections or old phones, this can take several seconds.",
            color: "#fbbf24",
          },
        ]}
      />
    </div>

    <p class="text-zinc-400 leading-relaxed">
      This is fine for dashboards and apps behind a login. But for public
      pages — a blog, a storefront, a landing page — those seconds of blank
      screen hurt. And search engines (Google) may not index
      JavaScript-rendered content well.
    </p>
  </div>

  {/* The SSR solution */}
  <div class="space-y-4">
    <h3 class="font-display font-bold text-teal-300 text-xl">
      Server-Side Rendering (SSR): The Fix
    </h3>
    <div class="flex flex-wrap gap-3 items-center mb-2">
      <RunsBadge location="Your Server" color="emerald" />
      <span class="text-zinc-500 text-sm">then</span>
      <RunsBadge location="User's Browser" color="violet" />
    </div>
    <p class="text-zinc-400 leading-relaxed">
      With SSR, the server runs your React components <em>before</em> sending anything to the browser. It fetches the data, renders the
      HTML, and sends a complete page. The browser shows content
      immediately, then React "hydrates" (attaches event listeners) to make
      it interactive.
    </p>

    <div class="rounded-xl border border-teal-900/30 bg-teal-950/10 p-6">
      <SequenceDiagram
        steps={[
          {
            from: "Browser",
            to: "Server",
            label: "Requests the page",
            color: "#2dd4bf",
          },
          {
            from: "Server",
            to: "Database",
            label:
              "Server runs your React component AND fetches data — all on the server",
            color: "#34d399",
          },
          {
            from: "Server",
            to: "Browser",
            label:
              "Sends fully rendered HTML with real content — not an empty shell. User sees the page instantly.",
            color: "#2dd4bf",
            direction: "left",
          },
          {
            from: "Browser",
            to: "Browser",
            label:
              'React "hydrates" — attaches click handlers, makes the page interactive. Page was already visible.',
            color: "#a78bfa",
          },
        ]}
      />
    </div>
  </div>

  {/* The rendering spectrum */}
  <DiagramBox>
    <div class="text-center mb-4">
      <span class="text-xs font-mono text-zinc-400 uppercase tracking-widest">
        The spectrum of rendering approaches
      </span>
    </div>
    <div class="flex flex-col md:flex-row gap-4">
      {/* CSR */}
      <div class="flex-1 rounded-xl border-2 border-violet-700/40 bg-violet-950/20 p-4 space-y-2">
        <div class="text-xs font-mono text-violet-400 font-bold uppercase tracking-wider">
          Client-Side Rendering (CSR)
        </div>
        <div class="text-lg font-display font-bold text-violet-300">
          Vite + React
        </div>
        <p class="text-sm text-zinc-400 leading-relaxed">
          Server sends an empty HTML shell. Browser downloads JS, React
          builds the entire page. All rendering happens in the browser.
        </p>
        <div class="text-xs text-zinc-400 pt-2 border-t border-violet-900/30 space-y-1">
          <div class="flex gap-2">
            <span class="text-emerald-400">+</span> Simple mental model,
            easy to deploy (static files)
          </div>
          <div class="flex gap-2">
            <span class="text-red-400">−</span> Blank screen until JS
            loads, poor SEO
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>

      {/* SSR */}
      <div class="flex-1 rounded-xl border-2 border-teal-700/40 bg-teal-950/20 p-4 space-y-2">
        <div class="text-xs font-mono text-teal-400 font-bold uppercase tracking-wider">
          Server-Side Rendering (SSR)
        </div>
        <div class="text-lg font-display font-bold text-teal-300">
          Next.js / Remix
        </div>
        <p class="text-sm text-zinc-400 leading-relaxed">
          Server runs React and sends <em>fully rendered HTML</em>. Browser
          receives a complete page instantly, then React hydrates to make it
          interactive.
        </p>
        <div class="text-xs text-zinc-400 pt-2 border-t border-teal-900/30 space-y-1">
          <div class="flex gap-2">
            <span class="text-emerald-400">+</span> Fast first paint,
            great SEO, link previews work
          </div>
          <div class="flex gap-2">
            <span class="text-red-400">−</span> Needs a running server,
            more complex deployment
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>

      {/* SSG */}
      <div class="flex-1 rounded-xl border-2 border-amber-700/40 bg-amber-950/20 p-4 space-y-2">
        <div class="text-xs font-mono text-amber-400 font-bold uppercase tracking-wider">
          Static Site Generation (SSG)
        </div>
        <div class="text-lg font-display font-bold text-amber-300">
          Next.js / Astro
        </div>
        <p class="text-sm text-zinc-400 leading-relaxed">
          Pages are rendered to HTML at <em>build time</em>, not at request
          time. No server needed at runtime — just static files, but with
          real content baked in.
        </p>
        <div class="text-xs text-zinc-400 pt-2 border-t border-amber-900/30 space-y-1">
          <div class="flex gap-2">
            <span class="text-emerald-400">+</span> Fastest possible,
            cheapest hosting, great SEO
          </div>
          <div class="flex gap-2">
            <span class="text-red-400">−</span> Content is stale until
            next build, not for dynamic data
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </DiagramBox>

  {/* What Next.js code looks like */}
  <div class="space-y-4">
    <h3 class="font-display font-bold text-teal-300 text-xl">
      What Does This Look Like in Code?
    </h3>
    <p class="text-zinc-400 leading-relaxed">
      In Next.js (App Router), components are
      <strong class="text-teal-200">
        server components by default
      </strong>
      . They run on the server and can directly access databases, read
      files, or call internal services — things a browser can never do. The
      component looks like normal React, but the framework runs it on the
      server and sends the rendered HTML to the browser.
    </p>

    <CodeBlock
      title="app/posts/page.tsx — Next.js server component"
      accent="teal"
    >
      <Fragment set:html={serverComponentCode} />
    </CodeBlock>

    <Callout color="#2dd4bf" icon="🤯">
      <strong class="text-teal-300">
        This component queries a database directly.
      </strong>
      No
      <code class="font-mono text-xs bg-zinc-800 px-1 rounded">
        useState
      </code>
      , no
      <code class="font-mono text-xs bg-zinc-800 px-1 rounded">
        useEffect
      </code>
      , no
      <code class="font-mono text-xs bg-zinc-800 px-1 rounded">
        fetch()
      </code>
      to an API, no
      <code class="font-mono text-xs bg-zinc-800 px-1 rounded">
        useQuery
      </code>
      . The SQL runs on the server, the JSX is rendered to HTML on the
      server, and the browser receives a finished page. Your database
      credentials and query logic never leave the server — the browser only
      gets the resulting HTML. The component is
      <code class="font-mono text-xs bg-zinc-800 px-1 rounded">
        async
      </code>
      — something not possible in client-side React.
    </Callout>
  </div>

  {/* When to use what */}
  <div class="space-y-4">
    <h3 class="font-display font-bold text-teal-300 text-xl">
      When to Use What
    </h3>
    <div class="grid md:grid-cols-2 gap-4">
      {[
        {
          title: "Use CSR (Vite + React) when...",
          color: "#a78bfa",
          items: [
            "Building a dashboard or admin panel",
            "The app is behind authentication (no SEO needed)",
            "You want the simplest possible setup",
            "You already have a separate backend API",
            "You're learning and want a clear client/server split",
          ],
        },
        {
          title: "Use SSR/SSG (Next.js) when...",
          color: "#2dd4bf",
          items: [
            "Building a public-facing website (blog, storefront, docs)",
            "SEO matters — you need Google to index your content",
            "First-load performance is critical (e-commerce)",
            "You want link previews on social media to work",
            "You want one codebase for frontend + backend logic",
          ],
        },
      ].map((col) => (
        <div
          class="rounded-xl border p-5"
          style={`border-color: ${col.color}30; background-color: ${col.color}08;`}
        >
          <h3
            class="font-display font-bold mb-3"
            style={`color: ${col.color};`}
          >
            {col.title}
          </h3>
          <ul class="space-y-2">
            {col.items.map((item) => (
              <li class="flex gap-2 text-sm text-zinc-400">
                <span
                  style={`color: ${col.color};`}
                  class="flex-shrink-0"
                >
                  ▸
                </span>
                {item}
              </li>
            ))}
          </ul>
        </div>
      ))}
    </div>
  </div>

  <Callout color="#2dd4bf" icon="💡">
    <strong class="text-teal-300">
      They're not competing — they're tradeoffs.
    </strong>
    Many teams use both: a Next.js app for their public marketing site and a
    Vite + React SPA for their logged-in dashboard. The right choice depends
    on your use case, not which is "better." Understanding CSR first makes
    SSR much easier to learn, because you already know what React is doing —
    SSR just moves <em>where</em> it does it.
  </Callout>
</div>
